DESCRIPTION:The holiest day of the Jewish year — a 25-hour fast of prayer and repentance seeking forgiveness for sins of the past year. Commanded in Leviticus 16 and 23.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20361001
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20361003
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sukkot-2036@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Sukkot (Feast of Tabernacles / Booths)
DESCRIPTION:A 7-day harvest festival where families build and dwell in temporary booths\, commemorating the Israelites' wandering in the wilderness after the Exodus. Commanded in Leviticus 23.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20361006
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20361014
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hanukkah-2036@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Hanukkah (Feast of Dedication)
DESCRIPTION:Eight-day festival celebrating the rededication of the Temple after the Maccabean revolt (~165 BC). Known as the Festival of Lights. Referenced in John 10:22 when Jesus walked in the Temple during this feast.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20361212
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20361221
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:purim-2037@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Purim
DESCRIPTION:Celebrates the deliverance of the Jewish people from Haman's plot as recorded in the Book of Esther. Observed with feasting\, gift-giving\, and reading the Megillah.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20370228
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20370302
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:passover-2037@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Passover / Feast of Unleavened Bread
DESCRIPTION:Commemorates the Exodus from Egypt. The Seder meal on the first night recalls the Passover lamb and deliverance from slavery. Seven days of unleavened bread follow.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20370330
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20370408
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:shavuot-2037@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Shavuot (Feast of Weeks)
DESCRIPTION:Celebrates the giving of the Torah at Mount Sinai\, occurring 50 days after Passover. One of the three major pilgrimage festivals commanded in the Torah.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20370519
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20370522
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:roshhashanah-2037@customcalendar
SUMMARY:Rosh Hashanah (Feast of Trumpets)
DESCRIPTION:The Jewish New Year\, observed as a day of remembrance and trumpet blowing. Begins the ten Days of Awe leading to Yom Kippur.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20370909
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20370912
END:VEVENT

